history.content: IMO the workload for 53 is pretty light. I took it with frenkel and i spent around 5 hours per week outside class (didn't attend lectures; so in total ~8 hours per week including discussion). You can also enroll in both 53 and a breadth, see how it goes and drop one after the first week of class.

children.subject: I'm in EE126 + CS 170 right now, and I find it totally manageable. I'm taking another class which definitely has more workload than Math 53/working part time too. The hardest part for me was realizing that 126 deserves a lot of respect as a class. There's a lot of understanding that 170 is a time intensive class, so I expected that, but 126 really caught me off guard as one of the hardest classes I've ever taken. That being said, it's the most amazing, useful course I've ever taken. Both have weekly problem sets so as long as you start early and don't save both for the last minute, you'll be fine.
Does anyone have experience with taking 170 and 126 together?
Is CS170+EECS126+EE120 a feasible schedule? I am thinking of doing a part time job as well.

history.content: I'm currently enrolled in CS170, EECS126, and Math53 and was wondering if this schedule would be a bit too much. On top of classes, I am also hoping to TA for another CS class so that would be another 8 hours of commitment a week. I got an A in CS70 but felt the probability part was my weakest so I really hope to improve my mastery on the subject by taking 126. Would it be wise to drop Math53 in exchange for maybe IEOR135 or a breadth and maybe take 53 over the summer instead?
